{"title_page": "Simon Russell Beale", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = [[Sir]]\n| name               = Simon Russell Beale\n| honorific_suffix   = [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]]\n| image              = Simon Russell Beale.jpg\n| caption            = Beale in 2011\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1961|01|12}}\n| birth_place        = [[Penang]], [[Federation of Malaya|Malaya]] {{small|(now Malaysia)}}\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Actor|author|historian}}\n| education          = [[Gonville and Caius College, Cambridge]]<br>[[Guildhall School of Music and Drama]]\n| residence          = [[London]], England\n| years_active       = 1985\u2013present\n| module             = <center>{{Listen|embed=yes|filename=Simon Russell Beale BBC Radio4 Desert Island Discs 08 July 2007 b007rwff.flac|title=<center>Simon Russell Beale's voice</center>|type=speech|description=<center>[[:File:Simon Russell Beale BBC Radio4 Desert Island Discs 08 July 2007 b007rwff.flac|Recorded July 2007]] from the BBC Radio 4 programme ''[[Desert Island Discs]]''</center>}}</center>\n}}\n'''Sir Simon Russell Beale''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CBE}} (born 12 January 1961) is an English [[Shakespearean actor|actor]], author and music historian.{{clarify|date=March 2020|reason=In what sense is he either an author or a music historian? There's nothing in the article to justify either label. See Talk.}}\n\nBeale has been described by ''[[The Independent]]'' as \"the greatest stage actor of his generation\".<ref>{{cite news | author=David Lister | title=Inside the World of Theatre's Most Reluctant Hero  | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/features/inside-the-world-of-theatres-most-reluctant-hero-785209.html | work=The Independent | date=22 February 2008 | accessdate=27 January 2009 | location=London}}</ref> He has appeared in ''[[Persuasion (1995 film)|Persuasion]]'' (1995), ''[[The Young Visiters#Adaptations|The Young Visiters]]'' (2003), ''[[Dunkirk (TV series)|Dunkirk]]'' (2004), ''[[The Deep Blue Sea (2011 film)|The Deep Blue Sea]]'' (2011) and as [[Falstaff]] in the [[BBC]] made-for-television films ''[[Henry IV, Part I and Part II (film series)|Henry IV, Part I and Part II]]'' (2012). He was part of the main cast of [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]'s ''[[Penny Dreadful (TV series)|Penny Dreadful]]''. More recently, he has appeared in [[Into the Woods (film)|''Into the Woods'']] (2014) and ''[[The Death of Stalin]]'' (2017).\n\n==Early years==\nBeale was born in [[Penang]], [[Federation of Malaya|British Malaya]], son of Lieutenant General [[Peter Beale (British Army officer)|Sir Peter Beale]] and Julia ''n\u00e9e'' Winter, where his father served in the [[Army Medical Services]], becoming [[Surgeon-General (United Kingdom)|Surgeon-General of HM Armed Forces]].<ref>{{cite web | title= Biography | url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/84/Simon-Russell-Beale.html | work=filmreference | year=2008 | accessdate=22 January 2009}}</ref> Several members of his family have pursued successful careers in medicine.\n\nBeale was first drawn to performance when, at the age of eight, he became a [[chorister]] at [[St. Paul's Cathedral]] and a pupil at the adjoining [[St Paul's Cathedral School (London)|St Paul's Cathedral School]]. His secondary education was undertaken at the independent [[Clifton College]] in [[Bristol]].\n\nHis first stage performance was as [[Hippolyta]] in ''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream]]'' at primary school.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Mick |last=Le Moignan |title=Generations in Harmony |journal=Once a Caian... |volume=15 |year=2015 |pages=12\u201313 |url=https://issuu.com/gonvillecaiuscollege/docs/once_a_caian._issue_15 }}</ref> In the sixth form at Clifton he also performed in ''[[Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead]]'', a play in which he would later star at the National Theatre.\n\nAfter Clifton, he went to [[Gonville and Caius College, Cambridge]], and obtained a [[first class honours|first]] in English, after which he was offered a place to undertake a PhD. He pursued further studies at [[Guildhall School of Music and Drama]] graduating in 1983.\n\n==Career==\nBeale first came to the attention of theatre-goers in the late 1980s with a series of lauded comic performances, which were on occasion extremely camp, in such plays as ''The Man of Mode'' by [[George Etherege]] and ''Restoration'' by [[Edward Bond]] at the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] (RSC). He broadened his range in the early 1990s with moving performances as Konstantin in [[Anton Chekhov|Chekhov]]'s ''[[The Seagull]]'', as Oswald in [[Henrik Ibsen|Ibsen]]'s ''[[Ghosts (play)|Ghosts]]'', Ferdinand in ''[[The Duchess of Malfi]]'' and as Edgar in ''[[King Lear]]''. At the first annual [[Ian Charleson Awards]] in January 1991, he received a special commendation for his 1990 performances of Konstantin in ''The Seagull'', [[Thersites]] in ''[[Troilus and Cressida]]'' and Edward II in ''[[Edward II (play)|Edward II]]'', all at the RSC.<ref>\"Timely tributes for a new generation of actors\", ''[[Sunday Times]]'', 13 January 1991.</ref>\n\nIt was at the RSC that he first worked with [[Sam Mendes]], who directed him as Thersites in ''Troilus and Cressida'', as ''[[Richard III (play)|Richard III]]'' and as [[Ariel (Shakespeare)|Ariel]] in ''[[The Tempest]]'', in the last of which he revealed a fine tenor voice. Mendes also directed him as [[Iago]] in ''[[Othello]]'' at the [[Royal National Theatre]] and in Mendes's farewell productions at the [[Donmar Warehouse]] in 2002, Chekhov's ''[[Uncle Vanya]]'', in which Beale played the title role, and ''[[Twelfth Night]]'', in which he played [[Malvolio]]. He won the 2003 [[Laurence Olivier Award]] for ''Uncle Vanya''.\n\nSince 1995, he has been a regular at the National Theatre, where his roles have included Mosca in [[Ben Jonson]]'s ''[[Volpone]]'' opposite [[Michael Gambon]], George in [[Tom Stoppard]]'s ''[[Jumpers (play)|Jumpers]]'' and the lead in ''[[Humble Boy]]'' by Charlotte Jones, a part written specially for him.\n\nIn 1997, he played the pivotal role of [[Kenneth Widmerpool]] in a television adaptation of [[Anthony Powell]]'s ''[[A Dance to the Music of Time]]'', for which he won the Best Actor award at the [[British Academy Television Awards]] in 1998.\n\nIn 1999, he was a key part of [[Trevor Nunn]]'s ensemble, playing in [[Leonard Bernstein]]'s ''[[Candide (operetta)|Candide]]'' (Voltaire/Pangloss), [[Edward Bulwer-Lytton]]'s ''Money'' and [[Maxim Gorky]]'s ''Summerfolk'' at the National. In autumn 2006, he played [[Galileo Galilei|Galileo]] in [[David Hare (dramatist)|David Hare]]'s adaption of [[Bertolt Brecht|Brecht]]'s ''[[Life of Galileo]]'' and as Face in ''[[The Alchemist (play)|The Alchemist]]''. From December 2007 to March 2008, he played Benedick in ''[[Much Ado About Nothing]]'' directed by [[Nicholas Hytner]] and from February to July 2008, he played Andrew Undershaft in Hytner's production of Shaw's ''[[Major Barbara]]''; he then appeared in [[Harold Pinter]]'s ''[[A Slight Ache]]'' and ''[[Landscape (play)|Landscape]]''.\n\nIn 2000, he played Hamlet in a production directed by John Caird for the National Theatre, a role for which he was described by ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' as \"portly [and] relatively long in the tooth\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/theatre/what-to-see/ten-great-hamlets-of-our-time/|title=Telegraph \u2013 Hamlet|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> In 2005, Beale was directed by [[Deborah Warner]] as Cassius in ''[[Julius Caesar (play)|Julius Caesar]]'' alongside [[Ralph Fiennes]] as Antony. That same year, he played the title role in ''[[Macbeth]]'' at the Almeida Theatre. In 2007, he reprised his 2005 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] role as [[King Arthur]] in the [[Monty Python]] musical ''[[Spamalot]]'' at the [[Palace Theatre, London|Palace Theatre]], London.\n\nIn 2008, he made his debut as a television presenter, fronting the [[BBC]] series ''[[Sacred Music (TV series)|Sacred Music]]'' with [[Harry Christophers]] and [[The Sixteen]]. Various specials and a second series have since been produced; the most recent episode ''(Monteverdi in Mantua: The Genius of the Vespers)'' was broadcast in 2015.\n\nIn spring 2009, Beale and Sam Mendes collaborated on ''[[The Winter's Tale]]'' and ''[[The Cherry Orchard]]'', in which Beale played Leontes and Lopakhin respectively, at the [[Brooklyn Academy of Music]], later transferring to the [[Old Vic Theatre]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://theater2.nytimes.com/2009/02/23/theater/reviews/23winter.html?pagewanted=1|title=Alas, Poor Leontes (That Good King Has Not Been Himself of Late)|last=Bradley|first=Ben|date=23 February 2009|work=New York Times|accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/culturecritics/charlesspencer/5493239/The-Winters-Tale-The-Cherry-Orchard-at-the-Old-Vic-review.html|title=The Winter's Tale, The Cherry Orchard at the Old Vic, review|last=Spencer|first=Charles|authorlink=Charles Spencer (journalist)|date=10 June 2009|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|quote=Simon Russell Beale, for my money this country's greatest stage actor, stars in both shows|accessdate=25 June 2009|location=London}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2009 to 2010, he played [[George Smiley]] in the [[BBC Radio 4]] adaptation of all the [[John le Carr\u00e9]] novels in which Smiley featured. These were broadcast in nineteen 90-minute or 60-minute full cast radio plays.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/smiley-season/ |title=The Complete Smiley |accessdate=21 May 2010 |date=19 May 2009 |work=BBC Radio 4 |publisher=BBC }}</ref>\n\nFrom March to June 2010, he played Sir Harcourt Courtly in ''[[London Assurance]]'', again at the National. In August 2010, he appeared in the first [[West End theatre|West End]] revival of ''[[Deathtrap (play)|Deathtrap]]'' by [[Ira Levin]]. In March 2011, he made his debut with [[The Royal Ballet]] in ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]''. In October 2011, he returned to the National to star as [[Joseph Stalin]] in the premiere of ''[[Collaborators (play)|Collaborators]]'', for which he won Best Actor at the 2012 [[Evening Standard Award]]s.\n\nIn 2010\u201311, Beale played the Coalition [[Home Secretary]] William Towers in the two final series of [[BBC One]]'s spy drama, ''[[Spooks (TV series)|Spooks]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006mf4b/features/full-credits|title=BBC One \u2013 Spooks \u2013 Full Credits|work=BBC}}</ref>\n\nHe played the title role in ''[[Timon of Athens]]'' at the National Theatre from July to October 2012. The production was broadcast to cinemas around the world (as was ''Collaborators'' earlier) on 1 November 2012 through the [[National Theatre Live]] programme.<ref>[http://www.nationaltheatre.org.uk/70226/productions/timon-of-athens-cast-creative-team.html www.nationaltheatre.org.uk]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He starred in a revival of [[Peter Nichols]]' ''[[Privates on Parade]]'' as part of [[Michael Grandage]]'s new [[West End theatre|West End]] season at the [[No\u00ebl Coward Theatre]] from December 2012 to March 2013.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2159520/The-Michael-Grandage-Company-Judi-Dench-Jude-Law-David-Walliams-Daniel-Radcliffe.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | title=The West End revolution: Judi Dench, Jude Law, David Walliams and Daniel Radcliffe... for \u00a310 a seat!}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, he won the [[British Academy Television Award]] (BAFTA) for Best Supporting Actor for his performance as Falstaff in the BBC's [[The Hollow Crown (TV series)|The Hollow Crown]] series of TV films about Shakespeare's historical dramas [[Richard II (play)|''Richard II'']]; ''[[Henry IV, Part 1]];'' ''[[Henry IV, Part 2]];'' and [[Henry V (play)|''Henry V'']].<ref name=GRDN>{{cite news|title=TV Baftas 2013: all the winners|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2013/may/12/baftas-2013-all-the-winners|accessdate=13 May 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=12 May 2013|location=London}}</ref> \n \nHe appeared alongside [[John Simm]] in [[Harold Pinter]]'s ''[[The Hothouse]]'' at the [[Trafalgar Studios]] from May to August 2013, directed by [[Jamie Lloyd (director)|Jamie Lloyd]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/west-end-theatre/news/03-2013/simon-russell-beale-and-john-simm-star-in-lloyds-h_854.html |title=Simon Russell Beale & John Simm star in Lloyd\u2019s ''Hothouse'' |first=Rosie |last=Bannister |work=\"Whats On Stage |date=15 March 2013 |accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nFrom January 2014, he played the title role in ''[[King Lear]]'' at the National Theatre, directed once again by Sam Mendes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/07-2013/kate-fleetwood-anna-maxwell-martin-and-olivia-vina_31424.html |title=Kate Fleetwood, Anna Maxwell Martin and Olivia Vinall join Russell Beale in Mendes\u2019 ''Lear'' |first=Rosie |last=Bannister |work=Whats On Stage |date=26 July 2013 |accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref> Also from 2014 to 2016 he starred as a main cast member in Showtime's \"Penny Dreadful\", in which he played an eccentric Egyptologist.\n\nFrom May to July 2015, he starred in ''[[Temple (play)|Temple]]'', a new play at the [[Donmar Warehouse]] about the [[2011 United Kingdom anti-austerity protests]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.donmarwarehouse.com/whats-on/donmar-warehouse/coming-up/2015/temple|title=Temple|work=donmarwarehouse.com|access-date=9 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110025312/http://www.donmarwarehouse.com/whats-on/donmar-warehouse/coming-up/2015/temple|archive-date=10 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> In September and October 2015, he played [[Samuel Foote]] in ''[[Mr Foote's Other Leg (play)|Mr Foote's Other Leg]]'' at the [[Hampstead Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/hampstead-theatre-russell-beale-david-hare_37821.html |title=Simon Russell Beale and David Hare in new Hampstead season |first=Theo |last=Bosanquet |work=Whats On Stage |date=15 May 2015|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref> It transferred to the [[Theatre Royal Haymarket]] from October 2015 to January 2016.\n\nIn 2014, Beale was appointed the Cameron Mackintosh Professor of Contemporary Theatre at [[Oxford University]], based at [[St Catherine's College, Oxford|St Catherine's College]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stcatz.ox.ac.uk/node/244|title=The Cameron Mackintosh Professor of Contemporary Theatre |publisher=University of Oxford}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, Beale returned to the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] in Stratford-upon-Avon, to play Prospero in ''[[The Tempest]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/stratford-upon-avon-theatre/news/simon-russell-beale-to-feature-in-new-rsc-season_39484.html |title=Simon Russell Beale to feature in new RSC season |first=Daisy |last=Bowie-Sell |work=Whats On Stage |date=11 January 2016|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref> In June 2017, it transferred to the [[Barbican Centre]] in London. In July 2018, Beale returned to the National, starring opposite [[Ben Miles]] and [[Adam Godley]] in ''[[The Lehman Trilogy]]'', again directed by Mendes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/national-theatres-the-lehman-trilogy-will-star-sim_45560.html |title=Simon Russell Beale to star in National Theatre\u2019s ''The Lehman Trilogy''  alongside Ben Miles and Adam Godley|first=Alex |last=Wood |work=Whats On Stage |date=18 January 2018|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref> It transferred to the [[Piccadilly Theatre]] in the West End in May 2019.\n\nBeale starred in the title role of ''[[Richard II (play)|Richard II]]'' at the [[Almeida Theatre]] from December 2018 to February 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/simon-russell-beale-anne-washburn-almeida-2019_47643.html |title=Simon Russell Beale, Patsy Ferran and Anne Washburn return in Almeida's new season|first=Daisy|last=Bowie-Sell |work=Whats On Stage |date=20 September 2018 |accessdate=22 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBeale is a past president of the [[Anthony Powell Society]],<ref>[http://www.anthonypowell.org/home.php?page=G06 www.anthonypowell.org]</ref> a tribute to his portrayal of [[Kenneth Widmerpool]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Curtis|first1=Nick|title=Simon Russell Beale: Some people say that I\u2019m a national treasure. I'd rather be a Bond villain|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/simon-russell-beale-some-people-say-that-im-a-national-treasure-id-rather-be-a-bond-villain-6501407.html|accessdate=15 September 2014|newspaper=London Evening Standard|date=10 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nBeale is gay. In the ''[[Independent on Sunday]]'' 2006 [[Pink List]]&nbsp;\u2013 a list of the most influential gay men and women in the UK&nbsp;\u2013 he was placed at number 30.{{cn|date=June 2016}}\n\nHe was knighted by Queen Elizabeth II, at Buckingham Palace, on 9 October 2019.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Orlando (film)|Orlando]]''\n| Earl of Moray\n| \n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Persuasion (1995 film)|Persuasion]]''\n| Charles Musgrove\n| \n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Hamlet (1996 film)|Hamlet]]''\n| Second gravedigger\n| \n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Blackadder: Back & Forth]]''\n| [[Napoleon]]\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[The Gathering (2002 film)|The Gathering]]''\n| Luke Fraser\n| \n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[The Deep Blue Sea (2011 film)|The Deep Blue Sea]]''\n| William Collyer\n| \n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[My Week with Marilyn]]''\n| Mr. Cotes-Preedy\n| \n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Into the Woods (film)|Into the Woods]]''\n| Baker's Father\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Cunk on Shakespeare''\n| Himself\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[The Legend of Tarzan (film)|The Legend of Tarzan]]''\n| Mr. Frum\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[My Cousin Rachel (2017 film)|My Cousin Rachel]]''\n| Couch\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Death of Stalin]]''\n| [[Lavrentiy Beria]]\n| [[BIFA Award for Best Supporting Actor|British Independent Film Award for Best Supporting Actor]]\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Museum (2018 film)|Museum]]''\n| Frank Graves\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Operation Finale]]''\n| [[David Ben-Gurion]]\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Mary Queen of Scots (2018 film)|Mary Queen of Scots]]''\n| [[Robert Beale (diplomat)|Robert Beale]]\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Radioactive (film)|Radioactive]]''\n| [[Gabriel Lippmann]]\n| \n|-\n| TBA\n| ''[[Operation Mincemeat (film)|Operation Mincemeat]]''\n|\n| Filming\n|}\n\n===Television films===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[The Young Visiters]]''\n| [[Prince of Wales]]\n| \n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Dunkirk (TV series)|Dunkirk]]''\n| [[Winston Churchill]]\n| \n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Henry IV, Part I and Part II (film series)|Henry IV, Parts I & II]]''\n| [[Falstaff]]\n| [[British Academy Television Award for Best Supporting Actor]]\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''The Temptation of Franz Schubert''\n| [[Franz Schubert]]\n|  \n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Alice in Wonderland (1999 film)|Alice in Wonderland]]''\n| King of Hearts\n| \n|-\n|}\n\n===Television series===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[A Very Peculiar Practice]]''\n| Mark Stibbs\n| Episode: \"Art and Illusion\"\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''Downtown Lagos''\n| Heron \n| 3 episodes \n|-\n| 1993\n| ''The Mushroom Picker''\n| Anthony\n| 3 episodes \n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[A Dance to the Music of Time]]''\n| Kenneth Widmerpool\n| 4 episodes \n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[American Experience]]''\n| [[John Adams]]\n| Episode: \"America's First Power Couple\"\n|-\n| 2010\u201311\n| ''[[Spooks (TV series)|Spooks]]''\n| [[Home Secretary]]\n| 13 episodes \n|-\n| 2014\u201316\n| ''[[Penny Dreadful (TV series)|Penny Dreadful]]''\n| Ferdinand Lyle\n| 14 episodes \n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Vanity Fair (2018 TV series)|Vanity Fair]]''\n| John Sedley\n| 6 episodes \n|-\n|}\n\n==Selected theatre==\n*Konstantin, ''[[The Seagull]]'', Royal Shakespeare Company, Royal Shakespeare Theatre, Stratford-upon-Avon, England, 1991\n*Ariel, ''[[The Tempest]]'', Stratford, England, 1994\n*''[[The Duchess of Malfi]]'', Greenwich and West End, 1995\n*Mosca, ''[[Volpone]]'', Royal National Theatre, London, 1995\n*''[[Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead]]'', Royal National Theatre, 1996\n*Iago, ''[[Othello]]'', Royal National Theatre, 1997\u201398\n*Alfred Evelyn, ''Money'', Royal National Theatre, 1999\n*''Battle Royal'', Royal National Theatre, 1999\u20132000\n*Title role, ''[[Hamlet]]'', Brooklyn Academy of Music, New York City, 2001\n*''[[Humble Boy]]'', Royal National Theatre, 2001\n*Title role, ''[[Uncle Vanya]]'', Donmar Warehouse, London, 2002, then Brooklyn Academy of Music, 2003\n*Malvolio, ''[[Twelfth Night]]'', Donmar Warehouse, 2002\n*Sir Harcourt Courtly, ''[[London Assurance]]'', Royal National Theatre, 2010\n*[[Joseph Stalin]], ''[[Collaborators (play)|Collaborators]]'', Royal National Theatre, 2011<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-reviews/8863297/Collaborators-National-Theatre-review.html|title=Collaborators, National Theatre, review|last=Spencer|first=Charles|date=2 November 2001|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=9 November 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n*Timon of Athens, ''[[Timon of Athens]]'', Royal National Theatre, 2012\n*Captain Terri Dennis, ''[[Privates on Parade]]'', No\u00ebl Coward Theatre, 2012\u201313\n*Also appeared as Sir Politic Wouldbe, Volpone; title role, ''[[Richard III (play)|Richard III]]''; and in ''[[The Man of Mode]]''; ''[[Troilus and Cressida]]''; ''[[The Trousers (play)|Die Hose]]'', Traverse Theatre; ''The Death of Elias Sawney'', Traverse Theatre; ''Sandro Manon'', Traverse Theatre; ''Look to the Rainbow'', Apollo Theatre; ''[[Women Beware Women]]'', Royal Court Theatre; ''[[A Winter's Tale]]''; ''Everyman in His Humour''; ''The Art of Success''; ''[[The Fair Maid of the West]]''; ''Speculators''; ''[[The Storm (Ostrovsky)|The Storm]]''; ''The Constant Couple''; ''Restoration''; ''Some Americans Abroad''; ''Mary and Lizzie''; ''Playing with Trains''; ''[[Edward II (play)|Edward II]]''; ''[[Love's Labour's Lost]]''; ''[[King Lear]]''; ''[[Ghosts (play)|Ghosts]]''; ''[[Candide]]''; ''[[Summerfolk]]''.\n*Dean, ''Temple'', Donmar Warehouse, 2015\n*Samuel Foote, ''Mr. Foote's Other Leg'', Hampstead Theatre, 2015\n*Henry Lehman & Philip Lehman (among other small roles), ''The Lehman Trilogy'', National Theatre, 2018. Armory Theatre, New York 2019. Piccadilly Theatre, London 2019.\n\n==Patronage==\nBeale is a [[Patronage|patron]] of the following organisations:\n* [[English Touring Theatre]]<ref>[http://www.ett.org.uk/About_ETT/Patrons.html ETT website]</ref>\n* [[South London Theatre]]\n* [[London Symphony Chorus]]<ref name=\"LSO\">{{cite press release | url=http://www.lsc.org.uk/about/news/321 | title=New Patron for LSC | accessdate=20 December 2010 | date=14 December 2010 | publisher=London Symphony Chorus | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121225001217/http://www.lsc.org.uk/about/news/321 | archivedate=25 December 2012 }}</ref>\n* For Short Theatre Company<ref>[http://orpingtoncommunity.weebly.com/for-short-theatre-company.html For Short Theatre Co.]</ref>\n* Diamond Fund for Choristers <ref>https://fcm.org.uk/diamond-fund-choristers/about/dfc-patrons/</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n*1998 \u2013 [[British Academy Television Award for Best Actor|BAFTA Award for Best Television Actor]] \u2013 ''[[A Dance to the Music of Time]]''\n*2000 \u2013 [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor in a Musical]] \u2013 ''[[Candide]]''\n*2003 \u2013 Appointed a [[Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire|CBE]] in the [[2003 Birthday Honours]]\n*2003 \u2013 [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor]] \u2013 ''[[Uncle Vanya]]''\n*2005 \u2013 [[Honorary degree|Hon DLitt]] ([[University of Warwick|Warwick]])<ref>{{cite web |url=https://warwick.ac.uk/services/gov/hongrads/list |title=List of all Honorary Graduates and Chancellor's Medallists |website=www.warwick.ac.uk |publisher=University of Warwick |accessdate=26 March 2020 }}</ref>\n*2010 \u2013 [[Bencher|Honorary Bencher]] of [[Middle Temple]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.middletemple.org.uk/events|title=Diary of Events|publisher=Middle Temple|accessdate=18 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081210074204/http://www.middletemple.org.uk/Events|archivedate=10 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*2010 \u2013 [[Honorary degree|Hon DUniv]] ([[Open University]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www8.open.ac.uk/students/ceremonies/files/ceremonies/file/graduate-directory-2010.pdf|title=Conferment of Honorary Degrees and Presentation of Graduates|publisher=Open University|accessdate=12 November 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101008174609/http://www8.open.ac.uk/students/ceremonies/files/ceremonies/file/graduate-directory-2010.pdf|archivedate=8 October 2010 }}</ref>\n*2011 \u2013 Honorary [[Freedom of the City of London]] for services to drama<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityoflondon.gov.uk/Corporation/media_centre/news_2011/srb_freedom.htm|title=Granted the Freedom of the City of London|publisher=City of London|accessdate=12 January 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120129090038/http://www.cityoflondon.gov.uk/Corporation/media_centre/news_2011/srb_freedom.htm|archivedate=29 January 2012 }}</ref>\n*2013 \u2013 [[British Academy Television Award for Best Supporting Actor]] \u2013 ''[[Henry IV, Part I and Part II (TV films)|Henry IV, Parts I & II]]''\n*2015 \u2013 Cameron Mackintosh Visiting Professor of Contemporary Theatre, [[St. Catherine's College, Oxford]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stcatz.ox.ac.uk/|title=St. Catherine's College Homepage|publisher=St. Catherine's College|accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref>\n*2017 \u2013 [[British Independent Film Awards 2017|British Independent Film Award for Best Supporting Actor]] \u2013 ''[[The Death of Stalin]]''\n*2018 \u2013 Premio Shakespeare Award<ref>{{cite web|title=La Royal Shakespeare Company anuncia el premio que le entregamos a Simon Russell Beale. {{!}} Fundaci\u00f3n Romeo para las Artes Escenicas|url=http://www.fundacionromeo.org/la-royal-shakespeare-company-se-hace-anuncia-el-premio-que-le-entregamos-a-simon-russell-beale/|website=www.fundacionromeo.org|language=es-ES|authorlink=[[Fundaci\u00f3n Romeo Argentina]]}}</ref>\n*2019 \u2013 [[Knight Bachelor]] in the [[2019 Birthday Honours]] for services to drama<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62666|supp=y|page=B2|date=8 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Birthday Honours 2019: Olivia Colman and Bear Grylls on list |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-48543826 |work=[[BBC News]] |location= |date=8 June 2019 |access-date=8 June 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n*Trowbridge, Simon, ''The Company: A Biographical Dictionary of the Royal Shakespeare Company'', Oxford: Editions Albert Creed, 2010. {{ISBN|978-0-9559830-2-3}}.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n*{{IMDb name|750971}}\n*{{IBDB name}}\n*[http://www.nationaltheatre.org.uk/?lid=4859 National Theatre: Platforms]\n*[http://www.topix.net/who/simon-russell-beale Russell Beale news]\n*[http://www.broadway.com/gen/Buzz_Story.aspx?ci=526110 Broadway.com Interview]\n*[http://www.stratfordians.org.uk/ The Company: A Biographical Dictionary of the RSC: Online database]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150924121613/http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/29671/Simon-RUSSELL-BEALE ''Debrett's People of Today'']\n\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Simon Russell Beale\n|list =\n{{British Academy Television Award for Best Actor}}\n{{British Academy Television Award for Best Supporting Actor}}\n{{BIFA Award for Best Supporting Actor}}\n{{Evening Standard Theatre Award for Best Actor}} \n{{OlivierAward MusicalActor}}\n{{OlivierAward PlayActor}}\n{{OlivierAward PlaySupportingPerformance}}\n}}\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beale, Simon Russell}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:Actors awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Gonville and Caius College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Guildhall School of Music and Drama]]\n[[Category:Audiobook narrators]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (people)]]\n[[Category:Best Actor BAFTA Award (television) winners]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actor BAFTA Award (television) winners]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Critics' Circle Theatre Award winners]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:English male radio actors]]\n[[Category:English male Shakespearean actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English music historians]]\n[[Category:English television presenters]]\n[[Category:Fellows of St Catherine's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Gay actors]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Laurence Olivier Award winners]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from England]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Penang]]\n[[Category:People educated at Clifton College]]\n[[Category:People educated at St. Paul's Cathedral School]]\n[[Category:Royal Shakespeare Company members]]\n[[Category:English people of Malaysian descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = [[Sir]]\n| name               = Simon Russell Beale\n| honorific_suffix   = [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]]\n| image              = Simon Russell Beale.jpg\n| caption            = Beale in 2011\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1961|01|12}}\n| birth_place        = [[Penang]], [[Federation of Malaya|Malaya]] {{small|(now Malaysia)}}\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Actor|author|historian}}\n| education          = [[Gonville and Caius College, Cambridge]]<br>[[Guildhall School of Music and Drama]]\n| residence          = [[London]], England\n| years_active       = 1985\u2013present\n| module             = <center>{{Listen|embed=yes|filename=Simon Russell Beale BBC Radio4 Desert Island Discs 08 July 2007 b007rwff.flac|title=<center>Simon Russell Beale's voice</center>|type=speech|description=<center>[[:File:Simon Russell Beale BBC Radio4 Desert Island Discs 08 July 2007 b007rwff.flac|Recorded July 2007]] from the BBC Radio 4 programme ''[[Desert Island Discs]]''</center>}}</center>\n}}\n'''Sir Simon Russell Beale''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CBE}} (born 12 January 1961) is an English [[Shakespearean actor|actor]], author and music historian.{{clarify|date=March 2020|reason=In what sense is he either an author or a music historian? There's nothing in the article to justify either label. See Talk.}}\n\nBeale has been described by ''[[The Independent]]'' as \"the greatest stage actor of his generation\".<ref>{{cite news | author=David Lister | title=Inside the World of Theatre's Most Reluctant Hero  | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/features/inside-the-world-of-theatres-most-reluctant-hero-785209.html | work=The Independent | date=22 February 2008 | accessdate=27 January 2009 | location=London}}</ref> He has appeared in ''[[Persuasion (1995 film)|Persuasion]]'' (1995), ''[[The Young Visiters#Adaptations|The Young Visiters]]'' (2003), ''[[Dunkirk (TV series)|Dunkirk]]'' (2004), ''[[The Deep Blue Sea (2011 film)|The Deep Blue Sea]]'' (2011) and as [[Falstaff]] in the [[BBC]] made-for-television films ''[[Henry IV, Part I and Part II (film series)|Henry IV, Part I and Part II]]'' (2012). He was part of the main cast of [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]'s ''[[Penny Dreadful (TV series)|Penny Dreadful]]''. More recently, he has appeared in [[Into the Woods (film)|''Into the Woods'']] (2014) and ''[[The Death of Stalin]]'' (2017).\n\n==Early years==\nBeale was born in [[Penang]], [[Federation of Malaya|British Malaya]], son of Lieutenant General [[Peter Beale (British Army officer)|Sir Peter Beale]] and Julia ''n\u00e9e'' Winter, where his father served in the [[Army Medical Services]], becoming [[Surgeon-General (United Kingdom)|Surgeon-General of HM Armed Forces]].<ref>{{cite web | title= Biography | url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/84/Simon-Russell-Beale.html | work=filmreference | year=2008 | accessdate=22 January 2009}}</ref> Several members of his family have pursued successful careers in medicine.\n\nBeale was first drawn to performance when, at the age of eight, he became a [[chorister]] at [[St. Paul's Cathedral]] and a pupil at the adjoining [[St Paul's Cathedral School (London)|St Paul's Cathedral School]]. His secondary education was undertaken at the independent [[Clifton College]] in [[Bristol]].\n\nHis first stage performance was as [[Hippolyta]] in ''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream]]'' at primary school.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Mick |last=Le Moignan |title=Generations in Harmony |journal=Once a Caian... |volume=15 |year=2015 |pages=12\u201313 |url=https://issuu.com/gonvillecaiuscollege/docs/once_a_caian._issue_15 }}</ref> In the sixth form at Clifton he also performed in ''[[Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead]]'', a play in which he would later star at the National Theatre.\n\nAfter Clifton, he went to [[Gonville and Caius College, Cambridge]], and obtained a [[first class honours|first]] in English, after which he was offered a place to undertake a PhD. He pursued further studies at [[Guildhall School of Music and Drama]] graduating in 1983.\n\n==Career==\nBeale first came to the attention of theatre-goers in the late 1980s with a series of lauded comic performances, which were on occasion extremely camp, in such plays as ''The Man of Mode'' by [[George Etherege]] and ''Restoration'' by [[Edward Bond]] at the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] (RSC). He broadened his range in the early 1990s with moving performances as Konstantin in [[Anton Chekhov|Chekhov]]'s ''[[The Seagull]]'', as Oswald in [[Henrik Ibsen|Ibsen]]'s ''[[Ghosts (play)|Ghosts]]'', Ferdinand in ''[[The Duchess of Malfi]]'' and as Edgar in ''[[King Lear]]''. At the first annual [[Ian Charleson Awards]] in January 1991, he received a special commendation for his 1990 performances of Konstantin in ''The Seagull'', [[Thersites]] in ''[[Troilus and Cressida]]'' and Edward II in ''[[Edward II (play)|Edward II]]'', all at the RSC.<ref>\"Timely tributes for a new generation of actors\", ''[[Sunday Times]]'', 13 January 1991.</ref>\n\nIt was at the RSC that he first worked with [[Sam Mendes]], who directed him as Thersites in ''Troilus and Cressida'', as ''[[Richard III (play)|Richard III]]'' and as [[Ariel (Shakespeare)|Ariel]] in ''[[The Tempest]]'', in the last of which he revealed a fine tenor voice. Mendes also directed him as [[Iago]] in ''[[Othello]]'' at the [[Royal National Theatre]] and in Mendes's farewell productions at the [[Donmar Warehouse]] in 2002, Chekhov's ''[[Uncle Vanya]]'', in which Beale played the title role, and ''[[Twelfth Night]]'', in which he played [[Malvolio]]. He won the 2003 [[Laurence Olivier Award]] for ''Uncle Vanya''.\n\nSince 1995, he has been a regular at the National Theatre, where his roles have included Mosca in [[Ben Jonson]]'s ''[[Volpone]]'' opposite [[Michael Gambon]], George in [[Tom Stoppard]]'s ''[[Jumpers]]'' and the lead in ''[[Humble Boy]]'' by Charlotte Jones, a part written specially for him.\n\nIn 1997, he played the pivotal role of [[Kenneth Widmerpool]] in a television adaptation of [[Anthony Powell]]'s ''[[A Dance to the Music of Time]]'', for which he won the Best Actor award at the [[British Academy Television Awards]] in 1998.\n\nIn 1999, he was a key part of [[Trevor Nunn]]'s ensemble, playing in [[Leonard Bernstein]]'s ''[[Candide (operetta)|Candide]]'' (Voltaire/Pangloss), [[Edward Bulwer-Lytton]]'s ''Money'' and [[Maxim Gorky]]'s ''Summerfolk'' at the National. In autumn 2006, he played [[Galileo Galilei|Galileo]] in [[David Hare (dramatist)|David Hare]]'s adaption of [[Bertolt Brecht|Brecht]]'s ''[[Life of Galileo]]'' and as Face in ''[[The Alchemist (play)|The Alchemist]]''. From December 2007 to March 2008, he played Benedick in ''[[Much Ado About Nothing]]'' directed by [[Nicholas Hytner]] and from February to July 2008, he played Andrew Undershaft in Hytner's production of Shaw's ''[[Major Barbara]]''; he then appeared in [[Harold Pinter]]'s ''[[A Slight Ache]]'' and ''[[Landscape (play)|Landscape]]''.\n\nIn 2000, he played Hamlet in a production directed by John Caird for the National Theatre, a role for which he was described by ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' as \"portly [and] relatively long in the tooth\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/theatre/what-to-see/ten-great-hamlets-of-our-time/|title=Telegraph \u2013 Hamlet|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> In 2005, Beale was directed by [[Deborah Warner]] as Cassius in ''[[Julius Caesar (play)|Julius Caesar]]'' alongside [[Ralph Fiennes]] as Antony. That same year, he played the title role in ''[[Macbeth]]'' at the Almeida Theatre. In 2007, he reprised his 2005 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] role as [[King Arthur]] in the [[Monty Python]] musical ''[[Spamalot]]'' at the [[Palace Theatre, London|Palace Theatre]], London.\n\nIn 2008, he made his debut as a television presenter, fronting the [[BBC]] series ''[[Sacred Music (TV series)|Sacred Music]]'' with [[Harry Christophers]] and [[The Sixteen]]. Various specials and a second series have since been produced; the most recent episode ''(Monteverdi in Mantua: The Genius of the Vespers)'' was broadcast in 2015.\n\nIn spring 2009, Beale and Sam Mendes collaborated on ''[[The Winter's Tale]]'' and ''[[The Cherry Orchard]]'', in which Beale played Leontes and Lopakhin respectively, at the [[Brooklyn Academy of Music]], later transferring to the [[Old Vic Theatre]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://theater2.nytimes.com/2009/02/23/theater/reviews/23winter.html?pagewanted=1|title=Alas, Poor Leontes (That Good King Has Not Been Himself of Late)|last=Bradley|first=Ben|date=23 February 2009|work=New York Times|accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/culturecritics/charlesspencer/5493239/The-Winters-Tale-The-Cherry-Orchard-at-the-Old-Vic-review.html|title=The Winter's Tale, The Cherry Orchard at the Old Vic, review|last=Spencer|first=Charles|authorlink=Charles Spencer (journalist)|date=10 June 2009|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|quote=Simon Russell Beale, for my money this country's greatest stage actor, stars in both shows|accessdate=25 June 2009|location=London}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2009 to 2010, he played [[George Smiley]] in the [[BBC Radio 4]] adaptation of all the [[John le Carr\u00e9]] novels in which Smiley featured. These were broadcast in nineteen 90-minute or 60-minute full cast radio plays.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/smiley-season/ |title=The Complete Smiley |accessdate=21 May 2010 |date=19 May 2009 |work=BBC Radio 4 |publisher=BBC }}</ref>\n\nFrom March to June 2010, he played Sir Harcourt Courtly in ''[[London Assurance]]'', again at the National. In August 2010, he appeared in the first [[West End theatre|West End]] revival of ''[[Deathtrap (play)|Deathtrap]]'' by [[Ira Levin]]. In March 2011, he made his debut with [[The Royal Ballet]] in ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]''. In October 2011, he returned to the National to star as [[Joseph Stalin]] in the premiere of ''[[Collaborators (play)|Collaborators]]'', for which he won Best Actor at the 2012 [[Evening Standard Award]]s.\n\nIn 2010\u201311, Beale played the Coalition [[Home Secretary]] William Towers in the two final series of [[BBC One]]'s spy drama, ''[[Spooks (TV series)|Spooks]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006mf4b/features/full-credits|title=BBC One \u2013 Spooks \u2013 Full Credits|work=BBC}}</ref>\n\nHe played the title role in ''[[Timon of Athens]]'' at the National Theatre from July to October 2012. The production was broadcast to cinemas around the world (as was ''Collaborators'' earlier) on 1 November 2012 through the [[National Theatre Live]] programme.<ref>[http://www.nationaltheatre.org.uk/70226/productions/timon-of-athens-cast-creative-team.html www.nationaltheatre.org.uk]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He starred in a revival of [[Peter Nichols]]' ''[[Privates on Parade]]'' as part of [[Michael Grandage]]'s new [[West End theatre|West End]] season at the [[No\u00ebl Coward Theatre]] from December 2012 to March 2013.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2159520/The-Michael-Grandage-Company-Judi-Dench-Jude-Law-David-Walliams-Daniel-Radcliffe.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | title=The West End revolution: Judi Dench, Jude Law, David Walliams and Daniel Radcliffe... for \u00a310 a seat!}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, he won the [[British Academy Television Award]] (BAFTA) for Best Supporting Actor for his performance as Falstaff in the BBC's [[The Hollow Crown (TV series)|The Hollow Crown]] series of TV films about Shakespeare's historical dramas [[Richard II (play)|''Richard II'']]; ''[[Henry IV, Part 1]];'' ''[[Henry IV, Part 2]];'' and [[Henry V (play)|''Henry V'']].<ref name=GRDN>{{cite news|title=TV Baftas 2013: all the winners|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2013/may/12/baftas-2013-all-the-winners|accessdate=13 May 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=12 May 2013|location=London}}</ref> \n \nHe appeared alongside [[John Simm]] in [[Harold Pinter]]'s ''[[The Hothouse]]'' at the [[Trafalgar Studios]] from May to August 2013, directed by [[Jamie Lloyd (director)|Jamie Lloyd]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/west-end-theatre/news/03-2013/simon-russell-beale-and-john-simm-star-in-lloyds-h_854.html |title=Simon Russell Beale & John Simm star in Lloyd\u2019s ''Hothouse'' |first=Rosie |last=Bannister |work=\"Whats On Stage |date=15 March 2013 |accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nFrom January 2014, he played the title role in ''[[King Lear]]'' at the National Theatre, directed once again by Sam Mendes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/07-2013/kate-fleetwood-anna-maxwell-martin-and-olivia-vina_31424.html |title=Kate Fleetwood, Anna Maxwell Martin and Olivia Vinall join Russell Beale in Mendes\u2019 ''Lear'' |first=Rosie |last=Bannister |work=Whats On Stage |date=26 July 2013 |accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref> Also from 2014 to 2016 he starred as a main cast member in Showtime's \"Penny Dreadful\", in which he played an eccentric Egyptologist.\n\nFrom May to July 2015, he starred in ''[[Temple (play)|Temple]]'', a new play at the [[Donmar Warehouse]] about the [[2011 United Kingdom anti-austerity protests]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.donmarwarehouse.com/whats-on/donmar-warehouse/coming-up/2015/temple|title=Temple|work=donmarwarehouse.com|access-date=9 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110025312/http://www.donmarwarehouse.com/whats-on/donmar-warehouse/coming-up/2015/temple|archive-date=10 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> In September and October 2015, he played [[Samuel Foote]] in ''[[Mr Foote's Other Leg (play)|Mr Foote's Other Leg]]'' at the [[Hampstead Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/hampstead-theatre-russell-beale-david-hare_37821.html |title=Simon Russell Beale and David Hare in new Hampstead season |first=Theo |last=Bosanquet |work=Whats On Stage |date=15 May 2015|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref> It transferred to the [[Theatre Royal Haymarket]] from October 2015 to January 2016.\n\nIn 2014, Beale was appointed the Cameron Mackintosh Professor of Contemporary Theatre at [[Oxford University]], based at [[St Catherine's College, Oxford|St Catherine's College]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stcatz.ox.ac.uk/node/244|title=The Cameron Mackintosh Professor of Contemporary Theatre |publisher=University of Oxford}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, Beale returned to the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] in Stratford-upon-Avon, to play Prospero in ''[[The Tempest]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/stratford-upon-avon-theatre/news/simon-russell-beale-to-feature-in-new-rsc-season_39484.html |title=Simon Russell Beale to feature in new RSC season |first=Daisy |last=Bowie-Sell |work=Whats On Stage |date=11 January 2016|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref> In June 2017, it transferred to the [[Barbican Centre]] in London. In July 2018, Beale returned to the National, starring opposite [[Ben Miles]] and [[Adam Godley]] in ''[[The Lehman Trilogy]]'', again directed by Mendes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/national-theatres-the-lehman-trilogy-will-star-sim_45560.html |title=Simon Russell Beale to star in National Theatre\u2019s ''The Lehman Trilogy''  alongside Ben Miles and Adam Godley|first=Alex |last=Wood |work=Whats On Stage |date=18 January 2018|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref> It transferred to the [[Piccadilly Theatre]] in the West End in May 2019.\n\nBeale starred in the title role of ''[[Richard II (play)|Richard II]]'' at the [[Almeida Theatre]] from December 2018 to February 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/simon-russell-beale-anne-washburn-almeida-2019_47643.html |title=Simon Russell Beale, Patsy Ferran and Anne Washburn return in Almeida's new season|first=Daisy|last=Bowie-Sell |work=Whats On Stage |date=20 September 2018 |accessdate=22 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBeale is a past president of the [[Anthony Powell Society]],<ref>[http://www.anthonypowell.org/home.php?page=G06 www.anthonypowell.org]</ref> a tribute to his portrayal of [[Kenneth Widmerpool]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Curtis|first1=Nick|title=Simon Russell Beale: Some people say that I\u2019m a national treasure. I'd rather be a Bond villain|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/simon-russell-beale-some-people-say-that-im-a-national-treasure-id-rather-be-a-bond-villain-6501407.html|accessdate=15 September 2014|newspaper=London Evening Standard|date=10 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nBeale is gay. In the ''[[Independent on Sunday]]'' 2006 [[Pink List]]&nbsp;\u2013 a list of the most influential gay men and women in the UK&nbsp;\u2013 he was placed at number 30.{{cn|date=June 2016}}\n\nHe was knighted by Queen Elizabeth II, at Buckingham Palace, on 9 October 2019.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Orlando (film)|Orlando]]''\n| Earl of Moray\n| \n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Persuasion (1995 film)|Persuasion]]''\n| Charles Musgrove\n| \n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Hamlet (1996 film)|Hamlet]]''\n| Second gravedigger\n| \n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Blackadder: Back & Forth]]''\n| [[Napoleon]]\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[The Gathering (2002 film)|The Gathering]]''\n| Luke Fraser\n| \n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[The Deep Blue Sea (2011 film)|The Deep Blue Sea]]''\n| William Collyer\n| \n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[My Week with Marilyn]]''\n| Mr. Cotes-Preedy\n| \n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Into the Woods (film)|Into the Woods]]''\n| Baker's Father\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Cunk on Shakespeare''\n| Himself\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[The Legend of Tarzan (film)|The Legend of Tarzan]]''\n| Mr. Frum\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[My Cousin Rachel (2017 film)|My Cou